4:
Oh my, looks like someone's getting
big. I swear your child was only this
tall last time I saw them.
6:
We dogfolk tend to grow faster,
that's all. But my, look at those
whiskers! My little one isn't the only
one growing, it seems.
8: Yeah! Your whiskers look so cool!
12:
Hmph... Look at those mangy cats.
Us soldiers are out here practically
beggin' for scraps while they live in
luxury.
13:
Looks like hoarding money is the
only thing those pests are good at...
16: You two, do you have a moment?
30:
Nevia? Sis? What are you doing here
with Alk and my bro Nimbus?
33:
Oh, so this is the sage I've heard so
much about.
38:
I apologize for the intrusion, but I
urgently need to speak with you, Sir
Albert.
43:
A map of the city, huh... What are
these red and blue marks?
46:
These are groups of insurgents...
Those who wish you two dead.
54:
Looks like it's about eighty percent
red dots and twenty percent blue...
Are the red dots for dogfolk groups
and the blue for catfolk groups?
57:
Correct. I used divination to discern
their approximate locations, after
which we were able to confirm their
whereabouts through interrogating
members.
60:
We have Alk and Nimbus to thank
for the latter. They were a great help.
64:
Please. Grabbin' a few collars and
scarin' a buncha cowards hardly
counts as work.
68: Now... how do we approach this?
70:
Should we rush in and arrest
everyone, or simply put them under
surveillance?
75:
But if we use too much force, more
groups will pop up. What do you
think, Sis?
83:
Perhaps we should try a kinder
approach.
86:
Of the dogfolk with ill will towards
the government, over half of them
are former soldiers. With peace, they
have returned to their homes, only
to be treated as a burden.
88:
A broken sword cannot return to
battle, and their pride as former
soldiers prevents them from seeking
help.
92:
Then we need to create a place in
society for them. Obviously that
means a home to live in, but also
food, employment—
100:
We cannot have them return to their
stations as soldiers, though. The war
has just ended, after all.
106:
You know, this is something that
Fiend fella mentioned, but...
108:
What about creating a military
group to help develop the lands
near the borders?
111:
I see... They could both protect the
towns in the area and work to
create farmlands and the like.
117:
So you seek reintegration over
senseless fighting... Yes, I think that
idea suits your regime quite nicely.
122:
We'll have to be careful when
devising roles and leaders, but we
can handle that. I shall start
recruiting soldiers immediately!
125:
So this must be why Claw left to
persuade you to join us, Sharp-Eyed
Sage.
128:
You have my thanks. I look forward
to your continued cooperation.
132:
My future is intertwined with yours,
so as do I.
140:
Hehe, have you forgotten? I told you
I would assist you.
143:
I would, however, like to ask you not
to call me "Sis."
148: Aw, but you're my sis, Sis!
152:
That... does not explain anything. But
I suppose it matters not...
156:
Please allow me to apologize for our
first meeting. 
I had lost sight of who I was.
161:
Whoa, come on, Sis! You don't need
to bow to me!
165:
In the past, I was merely holding
onto my anger at the world, others,
and myself...
167:
But I was burdened by the weight of
all that anger, which caused me to
run away from it...
169:
The days where I hide behind the
role of a wise sage end now.
173:
Does that mean you see a different
future now?
179:
However, the future I saw has been
delayed. Instead of being a year into
the future, it is now... slightly more
than a year off.
183: That's more than I could hope for.
185:
I'm not giving up any time soon.
We'll push that future back, little by
little...
188:
Until you don't see it happening for a
hundred—no, a thousand years!
194: We must do all we can.
197:
Thank you. I cannot tell you how
happy I am to have met you all.
